# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: storm-control
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] A **broadcast storm** or **broadcast radiation** is the accumulation of broadcast and multicast traffic on a computer network.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] Extreme amounts of broadcast traffic constitute a *broadcast storm*.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] It can consume sufficient network resources so as to render the network unable to transport normal traffic.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] A packet that induces such a storm is occasionally nicknamed a **Chernobyl packet**.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] Most commonly the cause is a switching loop in the Ethernet network topology (i.e. two or more paths exist between switches).
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] A simple example is both ends of a single Ethernet patch cable connected to a switch.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] As broadcasts and multicasts are forwarded by switches out of every port, the switch or switches will repeatedly rebroadcast broadcast messages and flood the network.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] Since the layer-2 header does not support a time to live (TTL) value, if a frame is sent into a looped topology, it can loop forever.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] When the spoofed packet arrives at the destination network, all hosts on the network reply to the spoofed address.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] The initial Echo Request is multiplied by the number of hosts on the network.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] This generates a storm of replies to the victim host tying up network bandwidth, using up CPU resources or possibly crashing the victim.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] In wireless networks a disassociation packet spoofed with the source to that of the wireless access point and sent to the broadcast address can generate a disassociation broadcast DOS attack.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] In a mobile ad hoc network (MANET), route request (RREQ) packets are usually broadcast to discover new routes.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] These RREQ packets may cause broadcast storms and compete over the channel with data packets.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-radiation] One approach to alleviate the broadcast storm problem is to inhibit some hosts from rebroadcasting to reduce the redundancy, and thus contention and collision.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] Broadcast traffic is used to transmit a message to any reachable destination in the network without the need to know any information about the receiving party.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] When broadcast traffic is received by a network switch it is replicated to all ports within the respective VLAN except the one from which the traffic comes from.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] Unknown-unicast traffic happens when a switch receives unicast traffic intended to be delivered to a destination that is not in its forwarding information base.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] In this case the switch marks the frame for flooding and sends it to all forwarding ports within the respective VLAN.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] Forwarding this type of traffic can create unnecessary traffic that leads to poor network performance or even a complete loss of network service.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] This flooding of packets is known as a *unicast flooding*.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] One issue that may arise is that some network devices cannot handle high rates of broadcast, unknown-unicast or multicast traffic.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] In such cases, it is possible to limit the BUM traffic for specific ports in order to have a control on the number of packets or bytes that are flooded on the VLAN to other devices.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] This threshold is represented in kilobits per second (kbps), and it can be set for broadcast rate, multicast rate and unknown unicast rate independently.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] In the case of unknown-unicast traffic, a security issue may arise.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] To prevent flooding unknown-unicast traffic across the switch, it is possible to configure the network equipment to divert unknown-unicast traffic to specific trunk interfaces in order to split broadcast coming from different VLANs or to use specific trunk interfaces for multiple VLANs.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] The use of VXLAN as overlay technology allows for providing data link layer connectivity services between endpoints that may be deployed across network layer network domains.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] Since those endpoints are logically part of the same data link layer domain, they must be capable of sending and receiving data link layer multi-destination frames (BUM traffic).
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] BUM traffic can be exchanged across network layer network boundaries by encapsulating it into VXLAN packets addressed to a multicast group, so to leverage the network for traffic replication services.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] In *Data Plane Learning* the broadcast traffic is flooded to multicast group members.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] In *Control Plane Learning* addresses are collected and forwarded via BGP.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] Broadcast traffic is reduced and VXLAN tunnel endpoints (VTEPs) reply to the caller directly.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] VXLAN can handle BUM in two ways: *Multicast* and *Head End Replication*.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] Multicast is the most common approach, and each VXLAN network identifier (VNI) is mapped to a single multicast group, while each multicast group may map to one or more VNIs.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] When a VTEP comes alive it uses the Internet Group Management Protocol to join the multicast groups for the VNIs it uses.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] When a VTEP has to send BUM traffic it will send it only to the relevant multicast group.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] Head End Replication is only available if using BGP EVPN.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] It is less efficient than multicast and does not scale well but it is simpler to implement if you do not have a multicast-enabled infrastructure.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] In Head End Replication, when BUM arrives, the VTEP creates several unicast packets and sends one to each VTEP that supports the VNI.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] Ethernet VPN (EVPN) and Provider Backbone Bridging EVPN (PBB-EVPN) provide Ethernet multipoint services over MPLS networks.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] In EVPN operations, the Provider Edge (PE) routers automatically discover each other when connected on the same Ethernet segment and select a Designated Forwarder (DF) responsible for forwarding BUM traffic.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] In a VXLAN-EVPN, MAC learning occurs via the *control plane* instead of *data plane*.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] Furthermore, it is accepted only traffic from VTEPs whose information is learnt via the control plane, otherwise it is dropped.
[src:storm-control/broadcast-unknown-unicast-and-multicast-traffic] This presents a secure fabric where traffic will only be forwarded between VTEPs validated by the control plane.
[src:storm-control/multicast] In computer networking, **multicast** is a type of group communication where data transmission is addressed to a group of destination computers simultaneously.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Multicast can be one-to-many or many-to-many distribution.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Multicast differs from physical layer point-to-multipoint communication.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Group communication may either be application layer multicast or network-assisted multicast, where the latter makes it possible for the source to efficiently send to the group in a single transmission.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Copies are automatically created in other network elements, such as routers, switches and cellular network base stations, but only to network segments that currently contain members of the group.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Network assisted multicast may be implemented at the data link layer using one-to-many addressing and switching such as Ethernet multicast addressing, Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM), point-to-multipoint virtual circuits (P2MP) or InfiniBand multicast.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Network-assisted multicast may also be implemented at the Internet layer using IP multicast.
[src:storm-control/multicast] In IP multicast, the implementation of the multicast concept occurs at the IP routing level, where routers create optimal distribution paths for datagrams sent to a multicast destination address.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Multicast is often employed in Internet Protocol (IP) applications of streaming media, such as IPTV and multipoint videoconferencing.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Ethernet frames with a value of 1 in the least-significant bit of the first octet of the destination address are treated as multicast frames and are flooded to all points on the network.
[src:storm-control/multicast] This mechanism constitutes multicast at the data link layer.
[src:storm-control/multicast] This mechanism is used by IP multicast to achieve one-to-many transmission for IP on Ethernet networks.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Modern Ethernet controllers filter received packets to reduce CPU load by looking up the hash of a multicast destination address in a table, initialized by software, which controls whether a multicast packet is dropped or fully received.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Ethernet multicast is available on all Ethernet networks.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Multicasts span the broadcast domain of the network.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Multiple Registration Protocol can be used to control Ethernet multicast delivery.
[src:storm-control/multicast] IP multicast is a technique for one-to-many communication over an IP network.
[src:storm-control/multicast] The destination nodes send Internet Group Management Protocol *membership report* and *leave group* messages, for example, in the case of IPTV when the user changes from one TV channel to another.
[src:storm-control/multicast] IP multicast scales to a larger receiver population by not requiring prior knowledge of who or how many receivers there are.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Multicast uses network infrastructure efficiently by requiring the source to send a packet only once, even if it needs to be delivered to a large number of receivers.
[src:storm-control/multicast] The nodes in the network take care of replicating the packet to reach multiple receivers only when necessary.
[src:storm-control/multicast] The most common transport layer protocol to use multicast addressing is User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:storm-control/multicast] By its nature, UDP is not *reliable*—messages may be lost or delivered out of order.
[src:storm-control/multicast] IP multicast is always available within the local subnet.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Achieving IP multicast service over a wider area requires multicast routing.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Many networks, including the Internet, do not support multicast routing.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Multicast routing functionality is available in enterprise-grade network equipment, but typically needs to be configured by a network administrator.
[src:storm-control/multicast] The Internet Group Management Protocol is used to control IP multicast delivery.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Application layer multicast overlay services are not based on IP multicast or data link layer multicast.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Instead, they use multiple unicast transmissions to simulate a multicast.
[src:storm-control/multicast] These services are designed for application-level group communication.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Internet Relay Chat (IRC) implements a single spanning tree across its overlay network for all conference groups.
[src:storm-control/multicast] The lesser-known PSYC technology uses custom multicast strategies per conference.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Some peer-to-peer technologies employ the multicast concept known as peercasting when distributing content to multiple recipients.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Explicit multi-unicast (Xcast) is another multicast strategy that includes addresses of all intended destinations within each packet.
[src:storm-control/multicast] As such, given maximum transmission unit limitations, Xcast cannot be used for multicast groups with many destinations.
[src:storm-control/multicast] The Xcast model generally assumes that stations participating in the communication are known ahead of time so that distribution trees can be generated and resources allocated by network elements in advance of actual data traffic.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Wireless communications (with the exception of point-to-point radio links using directional antennas) are inherently broadcasting media.
[src:storm-control/multicast] However, the communication service provided may be unicast, multicast, or broadcast, depending on if the data is addressed to an individual node, a specific group of nodes, or all nodes in the covered network, respectively.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Wireless networks use electromagnetic waves to transmit data through the air, enabling devices to connect and communicate without physical cables.
[src:storm-control/multicast] These networks come in various types, including Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, cellular, and satellite networks, each serving different purposes.
[src:storm-control/multicast] In digital television, the concept of multicast service sometimes is used to refer to content protection by broadcast encryption, i.e. encrypted pay television content over a simplex broadcast channel only addressed to paying viewers.
[src:storm-control/multicast] In this case, data is broadcast to all receivers but only addressed to a specific group.
[src:storm-control/multicast] The concept of *interactive multicast*, for example using IP multicast, may be used over TV broadcast networks to improve efficiency, offer more TV programs, or reduce the required spectrum.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Interactive multicast implies that TV programs are sent only over transmitters where there are viewers and that only the most popular programs are transmitted.
[src:storm-control/multicast] It relies on an additional interaction channel (a back-channel or return channel), where user equipment may send join and leave messages when the user changes TV channel.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Interactive multicast has been suggested as an efficient transmission scheme in DVB-H and DVB-T2 terrestrial digital television systems, A similar concept is *switched broadcast* over cable TV networks, where only the currently most popular content is delivered in the cable-TV network.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Scalable video multicast in an application of interactive multicast, where a subset of the viewers receive additional data for high-resolution video.
[src:storm-control/multicast] Another similar concept is Cell-TV, and implies TV distribution over 3G cellular networks using the network-assisted multicasting offered by the Multimedia Broadcast Multicast Service (MBMS) service, or over 4G/LTE cellular networks with the eMBMS (enhanced MBMS) service.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:storm-control/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] In communications, **traffic policing** is the process of monitoring network traffic for compliance with a traffic contract and taking steps to enforce that contract.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Traffic sources which are aware of a traffic contract may apply traffic shaping to ensure their output stays within the contract and is thus not discarded.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Traffic exceeding a traffic contract may be discarded immediately, marked as non-compliant, or left as-is, depending on administrative policy and the characteristics of the excess traffic.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] The recipient of traffic that has been *policed* will observe packet loss distributed throughout periods when incoming traffic exceeded the contract.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] If the source does not limit its sending rate (for example, through a feedback mechanism), this will continue, and may appear to the recipient as if link errors or some other disruption is causing random packet loss.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] The received traffic, which has experienced policing en route, will typically comply with the contract, although jitter may be introduced by elements in the network downstream of the policer.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] With reliable protocols, such as TCP as opposed to UDP, the dropped packets will not be acknowledged by the receiver, and therefore will be resent by the emitter, thus generating more traffic.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Sources with feedback-based congestion control mechanisms (for example TCP) typically adapt rapidly to static policing, converging on a rate just below the policed sustained rate.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Co-operative policing mechanisms, such as packet-based discard facilitate more rapid convergence, higher stability and more efficient resource sharing.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] As a result, it may be hard for endpoints to distinguish TCP traffic that has been merely policed from TCP traffic that has been shaped.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Where cell-level dropping is enforced (as opposed to that achieved through packet-based policing) the impact is particularly severe on longer packets.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Since cells are typically much shorter than the maximum packet size, conventional policers discard cells which do not respect packet boundaries, and hence the total amount of traffic dropped will typically be distributed throughout a number of packets.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Almost all known packet reassembly mechanisms will respond to a missing cell by dropping the packet entirely, and consequently a very large number of packet losses can result from moderately exceeding the policed contract.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] RFC 2475 describes traffic policing elements like a *meter* and a *dropper*.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] They may also optionally include a *marker*.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] The meter measures the traffic and determines whether or not it exceeds the contract (for example by GCRA).
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Where it exceeds the contract, some policy determines if any given PDU is dropped, or if marking is implemented, if and how it is to be marked.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Marking can comprise setting a congestion flag (such as ECN flag of TCP or CLP bit of ATM) or setting a traffic aggregate indication (such as Differentiated Services Code Point of IP).
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] In simple implementations, traffic is classified into two categories, or "colors" : compliant (green) and in excess (red).
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] RFC 2697 proposes a more precise classification, with three "colors".
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] In this document, the contract is described through three parameters: **Committed Information Rate** (CIR), **Committed Burst Size** (CBS), and **Excess Burst Size** (EBS).
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] A packet is "green" if it doesn't exceed the CBS, "yellow" if it does exceed the CBS, but not the EBS, and "red" otherwise.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] The "single-rate three-color marker" described by RFC 2697 allows for temporary bursts.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] The bursts are allowed when the line was under-used before they appeared.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] A more predictable algorithm is described in RFC 2698, which proposes a "double-rate three-color marker".
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] RFC 2698 defines a new parameter, the Peak Information Rate (PIR).
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] RFC 2859 describes the "Time Sliding Window Three Colour Marker" which meters a traffic stream and marks packets based on measured throughput relative to two specified rates: Committed Target Rate (CTR) and Peak Target Rate (PTR).
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] On Cisco equipment, both traffic policing and shaping are implemented through the token bucket algorithm.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Traffic policing in ATM networks is known as Usage/Network Parameter Control.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] The network can also discard non-conformant traffic in the network (using Priority Control).
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] The reference for both traffic policing and traffic shaping in ATM (given by the ATM Forum and the ITU-T) is the Generic Cell Rate Algorithm (GCRA), which is described as a version of the leaky bucket algorithm.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] However, comparison of the leaky bucket and token bucket algorithms shows that they are simply mirror images of one another, one adding bucket content where the other takes it away and taking away bucket content where the other adds it.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Hence, given equivalent parameters, implementations of both algorithms will see exactly the same traffic as conforming and non-conforming.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Traffic policing requires maintenance of numerical statistics and measures for each policed traffic flow, but it does not require implementation or management of significant volumes of packet buffer.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Consequently, it is significantly less complex to implement than *traffic shaping*.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Connection-oriented networks (for example ATM systems) can perform Connection Admission Control (CAC) based on traffic contracts.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] In the context of Voice over IP (VoIP), this is also known as Call Admission Control (CAC).
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] An application that wishes to use a connection-oriented network to transport traffic must first request a connection (through signalling, for example Q.2931), which involves informing the network about the characteristics of the traffic and the quality of service (QoS) required by the application.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] This information is matched against a traffic contract.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] If the connection request is accepted, the application is permitted to use the network to transport traffic.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] This function protects the network resources from malicious connections and enforces the compliance of every connection to its negotiated traffic contract.
[src:storm-control/traffic-policing-communications] Difference between CAC and traffic policing is that CAC is an *a priori* verification (before the transfer occurs), while traffic policing is an *a posteriori* verification (during the transfer).
